Dialogue: 0,0:01:35.94,0:01:39.75,English1,,0,0,0,,We were born into a mystery
Dialogue: 0,0:01:39.78,0:01:41.78,English1,,0,0,0,,one that has haunted us
Dialogue: 0,0:01:41.82,0:01:44.05,English1,,0,0,0,,since at least as long as we've been human.
Dialogue: 0,0:01:45.82,0:01:49.42,English1,,0,0,0,,We awakened on this tiny world
Dialogue: 0,0:01:49.46,0:01:52.36,English1,,0,0,0,,beneath a blanket of stars,
Dialogue: 0,0:01:52.39,0:01:55.70,English1,,0,0,0,,like an abandoned baby left on a doorstep
Dialogue: 0,0:01:55.73,0:01:58.20,English1,,0,0,0,,without a note to explain
Dialogue: 0,0:01:58.23,0:02:00.87,English1,,0,0,0,,where we came from, who we are,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:00.90,0:02:04.27,English1,,0,0,0,,how our universe came to be.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:04.31,0:02:08.57,English1,,0,0,0,,And with no idea how to end our cosmic isolation.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:08.61,0:02:12.28,English1,,0,0,0,,We've had to figure it all out for ourselves.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:17.92,0:02:19.95,English1,,0,0,0,,Best thing we had going for us
Dialogue: 0,0:02:19.99,0:02:21.42,English1,,0,0,0,,was our intelligence,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:21.46,0:02:25.12,English1,,0,0,0,,especially our gift for pattern recognition,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:25.16,0:02:27.43,English1,,0,0,0,,sharpened over eons of evolution.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:27.46,0:02:30.60,English1,,0,0,0,,The ones who were good at spotting prey and predator,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:30.63,0:02:34.13,English1,,0,0,0,,telling poisonous plants from the nourishing ones,
Dialogue: 0,0:02:34.17,0:02:37.17,English1,,0,0,0,,they had a better chance to live and reproduce.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:37.20,0:02:39.61,English1,,0,0,0,,They survived and passed on those genes
Dialogue: 0,0:02:39.64,0:02:41.01,English1,,0,0,0,,for pattern recognition
Dialogue: 0,0:02:41.04,0:02:43.11,English1,,0,0,0,,with its obvious advantages.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:43.14,0:02:45.68,English1,,0,0,0,,Cultures all over the planet
Dialogue: 0,0:02:45.71,0:02:48.35,English1,,0,0,0,,looked up at the same stars
Dialogue: 0,0:02:48.38,0:02:51.12,English1,,0,0,0,,and found different pictures there.
Dialogue: 0,0:02:58.16,0:03:00.59,English1,,0,0,0,,We used this gift for recognizing patterns in nature
Dialogue: 0,0:03:00.63,0:03:03.53,English1,,0,0,0,,to read the calendar in the sky.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:06.30,0:03:09.00,English1,,0,0,0,,The messages written in the stars
Dialogue: 0,0:03:09.04,0:03:10.87,English1,,0,0,0,,told our forefathers and mothers
Dialogue: 0,0:03:10.90,0:03:13.77,English1,,0,0,0,,when to camp and when to move on.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:13.81,0:03:15.38,English1,,0,0,0,,When the migratory herds
Dialogue: 0,0:03:15.41,0:03:17.38,English1,,0,0,0,,and when the rains and the cold would come.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:17.41,0:03:19.65,English1,,0,0,0,,And when they would cease for a time.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:19.68,0:03:21.65,English1,,0,0,0,,When they observed the direct connection
Dialogue: 0,0:03:21.68,0:03:23.18,English1,,0,0,0,,between the motions of the stars
Dialogue: 0,0:03:23.22,0:03:25.29,English1,,0,0,0,,and the seasonal cycles of life on Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:25.32,0:03:27.35,English1,,0,0,0,,they concluded, naturally,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:27.39,0:03:29.12,English1,,0,0,0,,that what happens up there
Dialogue: 0,0:03:29.16,0:03:31.52,English1,,0,0,0,,must be directed at us down here.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:31.56,0:03:33.36,English1,,0,0,0,,It makes sense, right?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:33.39,0:03:35.13,English1,,0,0,0,,If the sky was a calendar
Dialogue: 0,0:03:35.16,0:03:37.36,English1,,0,0,0,,and somebody stuck a Post-it note on top of it,
Dialogue: 0,0:03:37.40,0:03:40.30,English1,,0,0,0,,what else could it be but a message?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:40.33,0:03:43.50,English1,,0,0,0,,And so, when the heavenly order was suddenly violated
Dialogue: 0,0:03:43.54,0:03:47.31,English1,,0,0,0,,by the apparition of a comet in the sky...
Dialogue: 0,0:03:47.34,0:03:49.51,English1,,0,0,0,,they took it personally.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:49.54,0:03:51.41,English1,,0,0,0,,Can we really blame them?
Dialogue: 0,0:03:51.45,0:03:54.01,English1,,0,0,0,,Back then, they had no other logical explanation
Dialogue: 0,0:03:54.05,0:03:55.52,English1,,0,0,0,,for what was happening.
Dialogue: 0,0:03:55.55,0:03:57.15,English1,,0,0,0,,This was long before
Dialogue: 0,0:03:57.18,0:03:59.09,English1,,0,0,0,,anyone had yet to imagine Earth
Dialogue: 0,0:03:59.12,0:04:01.22,English1,,0,0,0,,as a spinning planet with a tilted axis,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:01.26,0:04:02.86,English1,,0,0,0,,revolving around the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:02.89,0:04:06.66,English1,,0,0,0,,Every ancient human culture made the same mistake,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:06.69,0:04:08.90,English1,,0,0,0,,a comet must be a message,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:08.93,0:04:11.73,English1,,0,0,0,,sent by the gods... or one particular god.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:11.77,0:04:15.03,English1,,0,0,0,,And almost invariably, our ancestors concluded
Dialogue: 0,0:04:15.07,0:04:18.87,English1,,0,0,0,,the news was not good.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:18.91,0:04:21.61,English1,,0,0,0,,It didn't matter if you were an ancient Aztec,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:21.64,0:04:26.35,English1,,0,0,0,,Anglo-Saxon, Babylonian, Hindu.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:26.38,0:04:29.75,English1,,0,0,0,,Comets were portents of doom.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:29.78,0:04:31.35,English1,,0,0,0,,The only difference among them
Dialogue: 0,0:04:31.39,0:04:33.65,English1,,0,0,0,,was the precise nature of the coming disaster.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:35.42,0:04:40.26,English1,,0,0,0,,"Dis-aster," as in the Greek word for "bad star."
Dialogue: 0,0:04:40.29,0:04:42.40,English1,,0,0,0,,To the Masai of East Africa,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:42.43,0:04:43.63,English1,,0,0,0,,a comet meant famine.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:43.66,0:04:45.47,English1,,0,0,0,,To the Zulu in the south,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:45.50,0:04:47.03,English1,,0,0,0,,it meant war.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:47.07,0:04:49.14,English1,,0,0,0,,To the Eghap people of the west,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:49.17,0:04:51.07,English1,,0,0,0,,it meant disease.
Dialogue: 0,0:04:51.11,0:04:52.31,English1,,0,0,0,,To the Djaga of Zaire,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:52.34,0:04:55.88,English1,,0,0,0,,specifically "smallpox."
Dialogue: 0,0:04:55.91,0:04:57.31,English1,,0,0,0,,To their neighbors, the Luba,
Dialogue: 0,0:04:57.34,0:05:01.08,English1,,0,0,0,,a comet foretold the death of a leader.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:01.12,0:05:05.08,English1,,0,0,0,,The ancient Chinese were remarkably systematic.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:05.12,0:05:08.99,English1,,0,0,0,,Starting in roughly 1400 BC,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:09.02,0:05:11.39,English1,,0,0,0,,they began recording and cataloguing
Dialogue: 0,0:05:11.43,0:05:13.13,English1,,0,0,0,,the apparitions of comets.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:13.16,0:05:14.56,English1,,0,0,0,,A three-tailed comet
Dialogue: 0,0:05:14.60,0:05:16.33,English1,,0,0,0,,meant calamity for the state.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:16.36,0:05:17.83,English1,,0,0,0,,A four-tailed comet
Dialogue: 0,0:05:17.87,0:05:20.13,English1,,0,0,0,,signified an epidemic was coming.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:20.17,0:05:22.97,English1,,0,0,0,,The human talent for pattern recognition
Dialogue: 0,0:05:23.00,0:05:25.00,English1,,0,0,0,,is a two-edged sword.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:25.04,0:05:27.51,English1,,0,0,0,,We're especially good at finding patterns,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:27.54,0:05:30.51,English1,,0,0,0,,even when they aren't really there--
Dialogue: 0,0:05:30.54,0:05:32.98,English1,,0,0,0,,something known as "false pattern recognition."
Dialogue: 0,0:05:37.28,0:05:39.19,English1,,0,0,0,,We hunger for significance,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:39.22,0:05:41.75,English1,,0,0,0,,for signs that our personal existence
Dialogue: 0,0:05:41.79,0:05:44.19,English1,,0,0,0,,is of special meaning to the universe.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:46.46,0:05:48.83,English1,,0,0,0,,To that end, we're all too eager
Dialogue: 0,0:05:48.86,0:05:50.96,English1,,0,0,0,,to deceive ourselves and others,
Dialogue: 0,0:05:51.00,0:05:54.50,English1,,0,0,0,,to discern a sacred image in a grilled cheese sandwich
Dialogue: 0,0:05:54.54,0:05:57.64,English1,,0,0,0,,or find a divine warning in a comet.
Dialogue: 0,0:05:57.67,0:06:00.37,English1,,0,0,0,,Today, we know exactly where comets come from
Dialogue: 0,0:06:00.41,0:06:03.74,English1,,0,0,0,,and what they're made of.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:05.68,0:06:07.48,English1,,0,0,0,,Our Ship of the Imagination,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:07.52,0:06:11.32,English1,,0,0,0,,fueled by equal parts of science and wonder,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:11.35,0:06:15.39,English1,,0,0,0,,can take us anywhere in space and time.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:15.42,0:06:17.79,English1,,0,0,0,,It can travel faster than light
Dialogue: 0,0:06:17.83,0:06:19.19,English1,,0,0,0,,and render visible those things
Dialogue: 0,0:06:19.23,0:06:21.19,English1,,0,0,0,,that cannot be seen.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:21.23,0:06:23.50,English1,,0,0,0,,It's carrying us to a mysterious realm
Dialogue: 0,0:06:23.53,0:06:26.17,English1,,0,0,0,,that lies one light-year from the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:27.37,0:06:29.40,English1,,0,0,0,,What is this swarm of worlds?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:29.44,0:06:31.87,English1,,0,0,0,,Was it organized by alien beings?
Dialogue: 0,0:06:31.91,0:06:33.14,English1,,0,0,0,,No.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:33.17,0:06:34.57,English1,,0,0,0,,Just gravity.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:34.61,0:06:37.01,English1,,0,0,0,,These are the snows of yesteryear,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:37.04,0:06:40.15,English1,,0,0,0,,drifting mountains of ice and rock,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:40.18,0:06:42.92,English1,,0,0,0,,the preserved remnants of the birth of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:42.95,0:06:45.15,English1,,0,0,0,,It's called the Oort Cloud,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:45.19,0:06:47.72,English1,,0,0,0,,after Jan Oort, the Dutch astronomer
Dialogue: 0,0:06:47.76,0:06:48.99,English1,,0,0,0,,who foretold its existence back in 1950.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:49.02,0:06:51.42,English1,,0,0,0,,who foretold its existence back in 1950.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:51.46,0:06:53.73,English1,,0,0,0,,He was trying to solve a paradox.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:53.76,0:06:57.06,English1,,0,0,0,,There's so many ways for comets to die.
Dialogue: 0,0:06:57.10,0:06:59.33,English1,,0,0,0,,Because they cross the orbits of planets,
Dialogue: 0,0:06:59.37,0:07:01.67,English1,,0,0,0,,comets frequently collide with them.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:01.70,0:07:04.67,English1,,0,0,0,,Comets are largely made of ice,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:04.71,0:07:06.51,English1,,0,0,0,,so every time they come near the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:06.54,0:07:09.51,English1,,0,0,0,,they lose a part of themselves through evaporation.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:09.54,0:07:11.91,English1,,0,0,0,,And after several thousand trips,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:11.95,0:07:13.95,English1,,0,0,0,,their ice is all gone,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:13.98,0:07:17.02,English1,,0,0,0,,and what remains of the comet is now an asteroid.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:17.05,0:07:19.95,English1,,0,0,0,,Comets can be gravitationally ejected from the solar system
Dialogue: 0,0:07:19.99,0:07:21.92,English1,,0,0,0,,and exiled into space.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:21.96,0:07:23.56,English1,,0,0,0,,And yet, somehow,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:23.59,0:07:25.39,English1,,0,0,0,,the comets keep coming.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:25.43,0:07:28.06,English1,,0,0,0,,Oort and other astronomers wondered,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:28.10,0:07:30.23,English1,,0,0,0,,"Where do all the comets come from?"
Dialogue: 0,0:07:32.57,0:07:35.57,English1,,0,0,0,,Oort calculated the rate at which new comets appear
Dialogue: 0,0:07:35.60,0:07:37.57,English1,,0,0,0,,and concluded that there must be
Dialogue: 0,0:07:37.61,0:07:39.37,English1,,0,0,0,,a vast, spherical swarm of them,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:39.41,0:07:41.57,English1,,0,0,0,,a few light-years across,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:41.61,0:07:44.01,English1,,0,0,0,,surrounding the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:46.08,0:07:49.55,English1,,0,0,0,,Oort's logic still holds up,
Dialogue: 0,0:07:49.58,0:07:51.95,English1,,0,0,0,,even after all the discoveries we've made about comets
Dialogue: 0,0:07:51.99,0:07:54.75,English1,,0,0,0,,and the solar system in the many decades since.
Dialogue: 0,0:07:54.79,0:07:57.76,English1,,0,0,0,,And yet, the Oort Cloud is a sight
Dialogue: 0,0:07:57.79,0:08:00.66,English1,,0,0,0,,that no one has ever seen.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:00.69,0:08:01.93,English1,,0,0,0,,Nor could we.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:01.96,0:08:04.23,English1,,0,0,0,,It's dark out here.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:04.27,0:08:07.33,English1,,0,0,0,,And each comet is about as far from its closest neighbor
Dialogue: 0,0:08:07.37,0:08:09.30,English1,,0,0,0,,as the Earth is from Saturn.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:09.34,0:08:12.51,English1,,0,0,0,,But science gives us special powers of our own.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:12.54,0:08:14.61,English1,,0,0,0,,It gave Jan Oort
Dialogue: 0,0:08:14.64,0:08:16.64,English1,,0,0,0,,the gift of prophecy.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:16.68,0:08:19.01,English1,,0,0,0,,Oort was also the first to correctly estimate
Dialogue: 0,0:08:19.05,0:08:20.98,English1,,0,0,0,,the distance between the Sun and the center of our galaxy.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:21.02,0:08:22.48,English1,,0,0,0,,the distance between the Sun and the center of our galaxy.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:22.52,0:08:24.45,English1,,0,0,0,,That's a big deal--
Dialogue: 0,0:08:24.49,0:08:26.82,English1,,0,0,0,,finding out where we are in the Milky Way.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:26.85,0:08:28.29,English1,,0,0,0,,Our star is about
Dialogue: 0,0:08:28.32,0:08:30.99,English1,,0,0,0,,30,000 light-years from the center.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:31.03,0:08:32.43,English1,,0,0,0,,Oort was also
Dialogue: 0,0:08:32.46,0:08:34.26,English1,,0,0,0,,the first guy to use a radio telescope
Dialogue: 0,0:08:34.30,0:08:36.60,English1,,0,0,0,,to map the galaxy's spiral structure.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:36.63,0:08:39.70,English1,,0,0,0,,And he discovered that the center of our galaxy
Dialogue: 0,0:08:39.73,0:08:43.14,English1,,0,0,0,,was a place of titanic explosions,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:43.17,0:08:44.37,English1,,0,0,0,,the first indication that there might have been
Dialogue: 0,0:08:44.41,0:08:45.87,English1,,0,0,0,,the first indication that there might have been
Dialogue: 0,0:08:45.91,0:08:47.94,English1,,0,0,0,,a supermassive black hole lurking there.
Dialogue: 0,0:08:47.98,0:08:49.61,English1,,0,0,0,,Does the fact that most of us know
Dialogue: 0,0:08:49.64,0:08:51.85,English1,,0,0,0,,the names of mass murderers,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:51.88,0:08:53.68,English1,,0,0,0,,but never heard of Jan Oort,
Dialogue: 0,0:08:53.71,0:08:55.92,English1,,0,0,0,,say anything about us?
Dialogue: 0,0:09:04.86,0:09:07.46,English1,,0,0,0,,The Oort Cloud is so enormous
Dialogue: 0,0:09:07.50,0:09:10.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that it takes one of its comets about a million years
Dialogue: 0,0:09:10.03,0:09:12.90,English1,,0,0,0,,to complete a single trip around the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:16.27,0:09:18.47,English1,,0,0,0,,Out here, at the far edge of the solar system,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:18.51,0:09:21.64,English1,,0,0,0,,even a little tug from the gravity of a passing star
Dialogue: 0,0:09:21.68,0:09:23.64,English1,,0,0,0,,can liberate some of these comets
Dialogue: 0,0:09:23.68,0:09:26.95,English1,,0,0,0,,from their gravitational bondage to the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:30.68,0:09:33.72,English1,,0,0,0,,Some comets are flung out of the solar system
Dialogue: 0,0:09:33.75,0:09:35.19,English1,,0,0,0,,to wander interstellar space.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:35.22,0:09:37.62,English1,,0,0,0,,But for others, there's a different fate.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:44.43,0:09:47.37,English1,,0,0,0,,This one is plunging towards the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:47.40,0:09:50.10,English1,,0,0,0,,gaining speed in an unbroken free fall
Dialogue: 0,0:09:50.14,0:09:52.57,English1,,0,0,0,,that lasts hundreds of thousands of years.
Dialogue: 0,0:09:54.44,0:09:56.68,English1,,0,0,0,,When Neptune's gravity gives it another tug,
Dialogue: 0,0:09:56.71,0:10:00.18,English1,,0,0,0,,there's a small change in course.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:00.21,0:10:01.75,English1,,0,0,0,,Mighty Jupiter, the most massive
Dialogue: 0,0:10:01.78,0:10:03.18,English1,,0,0,0,,object in our solar system--
Dialogue: 0,0:10:03.22,0:10:05.89,English1,,0,0,0,,other than the Sun-- attracts the comet
Dialogue: 0,0:10:05.92,0:10:07.92,English1,,0,0,0,,with its powerful gravitational pull, bending its path.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:07.96,0:10:10.39,English1,,0,0,0,,with its powerful gravitational pull, bending its path.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:13.73,0:10:18.36,English1,,0,0,0,,When our comet reaches the inner solar system...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:18.40,0:10:22.40,English1,,0,0,0,,heat from the Sun bakes it.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:29.74,0:10:33.48,English1,,0,0,0,,A beautiful transformation begins.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:33.51,0:10:36.25,English1,,0,0,0,,The barren, sooty iceberg
Dialogue: 0,0:10:36.28,0:10:39.75,English1,,0,0,0,,now sports a glowing halo...
Dialogue: 0,0:10:39.79,0:10:42.19,English1,,0,0,0,,and a tail.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:49.00,0:10:50.76,English1,,0,0,0,,These layers tell the story of how the comet was made,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:50.80,0:10:52.10,English1,,0,0,0,,These layers tell the story of how the comet was made,
Dialogue: 0,0:10:52.13,0:10:54.53,English1,,0,0,0,,some four billion years ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:10:58.97,0:11:02.64,English1,,0,0,0,,During the 40,000 generations of humanity,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:02.68,0:11:05.25,English1,,0,0,0,,there must have been roughly 100,000 apparitions
Dialogue: 0,0:11:05.28,0:11:07.01,English1,,0,0,0,,of a bright comet.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:07.05,0:11:08.92,English1,,0,0,0,,For all that time,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:08.95,0:11:13.75,English1,,0,0,0,,the best we could do was look up in helpless wonder,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:13.79,0:11:16.26,English1,,0,0,0,,prisoners of Earth with nowhere to turn
Dialogue: 0,0:11:16.29,0:11:19.39,English1,,0,0,0,,for an explanation beyond our guilt and our fears.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:21.06,0:11:24.26,English1,,0,0,0,,But then a friendship began between two men that led
Dialogue: 0,0:11:24.30,0:11:27.00,English1,,0,0,0,,to a permanent revolution in human thought.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:29.14,0:11:32.17,English1,,0,0,0,,Isaac Newton and Edmond Halley could not know it,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:32.21,0:11:35.94,English1,,0,0,0,,but their collaboration would ultimately set us free
Dialogue: 0,0:11:35.98,0:11:39.41,English1,,0,0,0,,from our long confinement on this tiny world.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:44.58,0:11:46.34,English1,,0,0,0,,The Comet of 1664
Dialogue: 0,0:11:46.38,0:11:49.95,English1,,0,0,0,,sent shivers of dread throughout Europe,
Dialogue: 0,0:11:49.98,0:11:52.52,English1,,0,0,0,,and the terror seemed justified when the Plague
Dialogue: 0,0:11:52.55,0:11:55.72,English1,,0,0,0,,and the Great Fire of London followed soon after.
Dialogue: 0,0:11:57.12,0:12:00.56,English1,,0,0,0,,There, with long bloody hair,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:00.59,0:12:03.86,English1,,0,0,0,,a blazing star threatens the world
Dialogue: 0,0:12:03.89,0:12:08.60,English1,,0,0,0,,with famine, plague and war.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:10.23,0:12:12.90,English1,,0,0,0,,To princes, it spells death...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:14.07,0:12:17.11,English1,,0,0,0,,to kingdoms, many crosses...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:17.14,0:12:21.41,English1,,0,0,0,,to all estates, inevitable losses...
Dialogue: 0,0:12:21.45,0:12:24.45,English1,,0,0,0,,to herdsmen, rot,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:24.48,0:12:27.32,English1,,0,0,0,,to plowmen, hapless seasons,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:27.35,0:12:31.92,English1,,0,0,0,,to sailors, it brings storms,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:31.96,0:12:35.93,English1,,0,0,0,,to cities, civil treasons.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:43.00,0:12:45.33,English1,,0,0,0,,But for one child,
Dialogue: 0,0:12:45.37,0:12:48.10,English1,,0,0,0,,the comet was not the least bit frightening.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:52.88,0:12:57.28,English1,,0,0,0,,For him, it was a thing of wonder.
Dialogue: 0,0:12:57.31,0:13:00.35,English1,,0,0,0,,Like all of us, Edmond Halley was born curious.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:00.38,0:13:02.49,English1,,0,0,0,,Hell's bells!
Dialogue: 0,0:13:02.52,0:13:05.62,English1,,0,0,0,,He was lucky to have a father who\Nencouraged and nurtured his curiosity,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:05.66,0:13:07.32,English1,,0,0,0,,He was lucky to have a father who\Nencouraged and nurtured his curiosity,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:07.36,0:13:10.36,English1,,0,0,0,,buying him the best scientific instruments
Dialogue: 0,0:13:10.39,0:13:12.30,English1,,0,0,0,,and even funding his expedition
Dialogue: 0,0:13:12.33,0:13:15.33,English1,,0,0,0,,to make the first accurate star\N{\i1}map of the Southern Hemisphere.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:15.37,0:13:18.20,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley dropped out of Oxford when he was 20,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:18.24,0:13:20.17,English1,,0,0,0,,and sailed to St. Helena,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:20.20,0:13:23.71,English1,,0,0,0,,an island below the equator,\N{\i1}off the west coast of Africa.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:29.05,0:13:30.81,English1,,0,0,0,,Hell's bells.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:30.85,0:13:32.95,English1,,0,0,0,,The problem was, nobody told Halley
Dialogue: 0,0:13:33.98,0:13:35.82,English1,,0,0,0,,that the weather on St. Helena
Dialogue: 0,0:13:35.85,0:13:38.86,English1,,0,0,0,,was generally lousy; it took\N{\i1}him 12 frustrating months
Dialogue: 0,0:13:38.86,0:13:43.83,English1,,0,0,0,,to observe enough southern\N{\i1}stars to make a complete map.
Dialogue: 0,0:13:43.86,0:13:47.86,English1,,0,0,0,,The gods and heroes of ancient Greece were now joined
Dialogue: 0,0:13:47.90,0:13:51.00,English1,,0,0,0,,by the mythic figures of a new world and age,
Dialogue: 0,0:13:51.04,0:13:55.20,English1,,0,0,0,,a toucan, a compass,\N{\i1}a bird of paradise.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:03.58,0:14:06.58,English1,,0,0,0,,When Halley came home\Nwith the other half of the sky,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:06.62,0:14:08.55,English1,,0,0,0,,his map created a sensation.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:08.59,0:14:11.72,English1,,0,0,0,,Now merchants and explorers could navigate\Nby the stars visible anywhere on Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:11.76,0:14:13.49,English1,,0,0,0,,Now merchants and explorers could navigate\Nby the stars visible anywhere on Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:13.52,0:14:16.56,English1,,0,0,0,,At the time, the World Society of London
Dialogue: 0,0:14:16.59,0:14:18.76,English1,,0,0,0,,was the world's clearinghouse of scientific discovery.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:18.80,0:14:21.53,English1,,0,0,0,,Its motto,{\i1} "Nullius in verba,"
Dialogue: 0,0:14:21.57,0:14:24.27,English1,,0,0,0,,sums up the heart of the scientific method.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:24.30,0:14:27.27,English1,,0,0,0,,It's Latin for "see for yourself."
Dialogue: 0,0:14:27.30,0:14:30.94,English1,,0,0,0,,In other words, "question authority."
Dialogue: 0,0:14:30.97,0:14:32.61,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley's star maps caught the attention
Dialogue: 0,0:14:32.64,0:14:34.91,English1,,0,0,0,,of the Society's Curator of Experiments.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:34.95,0:14:36.68,English1,,0,0,0,,I'd show him to you if I could,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:36.71,0:14:39.75,English1,,0,0,0,,but no portrait of Robert Hooke exists from his time,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:39.78,0:14:42.75,English1,,0,0,0,,only the verbal descriptions of his contemporaries.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:42.79,0:14:46.06,English1,,0,0,0,,They called him "lean, bent, ugly."
Dialogue: 0,0:14:46.09,0:14:49.19,English1,,0,0,0,,He was possibly the most\Ninventive person who ever lived.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:49.23,0:14:50.96,English1,,0,0,0,,And despite his appearance,
Dialogue: 0,0:14:50.99,0:14:54.10,English1,,0,0,0,,he was the most sought-after\Nparty guest in all of London.
Dialogue: 0,0:14:54.13,0:14:55.87,English1,,0,0,0,,Why?
Dialogue: 0,0:14:55.90,0:14:58.37,English1,,0,0,0,,Hooke's insatiable curiosity
Dialogue: 0,0:14:58.40,0:15:00.44,English1,,0,0,0,,encompassed absolutely everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:02.57,0:15:05.41,English1,,0,0,0,,Hooke discovered a little cosmos,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:05.44,0:15:08.78,English1,,0,0,0,,and we still call it by the name he gave it, the cell.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:08.81,0:15:10.58,English1,,0,0,0,,Hooke discovered the cell by looking
Dialogue: 0,0:15:10.61,0:15:13.32,English1,,0,0,0,,at a piece of cork with one of his own inventions,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:13.35,0:15:15.79,English1,,0,0,0,,the compound microscope.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:15.82,0:15:19.12,English1,,0,0,0,,He anticipated aspects of\N{\i1}Darwin's theory of evolution
Dialogue: 0,0:15:19.16,0:15:22.23,English1,,0,0,0,,by almost 200 years.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:22.26,0:15:24.33,English1,,0,0,0,,Hooke also improved the telescope.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:24.36,0:15:26.96,English1,,0,0,0,,The drawings he made of the\N{\i1}astronomical bodies he observed
Dialogue: 0,0:15:27.00,0:15:29.10,English1,,0,0,0,,attest to his uncanny precision.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:29.13,0:15:33.60,English1,,0,0,0,,After the Great Fire destroyed\N{\i1}central London in 1666,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:33.64,0:15:36.41,English1,,0,0,0,,Hooke partnered with the architect Christopher Wren
Dialogue: 0,0:15:36.44,0:15:39.48,English1,,0,0,0,,to redesign and rebuild the city.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:39.51,0:15:43.41,English1,,0,0,0,,Hooke was the foremost experimentalist of his age.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:43.45,0:15:44.78,English1,,0,0,0,,Using coiled springs,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:44.82,0:15:46.52,English1,,0,0,0,,he derived the "law of elasticity,"
Dialogue: 0,0:15:46.55,0:15:49.02,English1,,0,0,0,,known today as Hooke's Law.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:49.05,0:15:51.49,English1,,0,0,0,,He perfected the air pump,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:51.52,0:15:53.86,English1,,0,0,0,,the height of technology in its time,
Dialogue: 0,0:15:53.89,0:15:57.63,English1,,0,0,0,,and used it to experiment on respiration and sound.
Dialogue: 0,0:15:57.66,0:16:00.66,English1,,0,0,0,,And he experimented with cannabis.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:00.70,0:16:03.33,English1,,0,0,0,,He reported to a meeting\No{\i1}f the Royal Society
Dialogue: 0,0:16:03.37,0:16:06.00,English1,,0,0,0,,that a sea captain friend of his
Dialogue: 0,0:16:06.04,0:16:08.60,English1,,0,0,0,,"had so often experimented with it,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:08.64,0:16:10.21,English1,,0,0,0,,that there is no cause of fear,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:10.24,0:16:13.14,English1,,0,0,0,,though possibly there may be of laughter."
Dialogue: 0,0:16:17.38,0:16:20.02,English1,,0,0,0,,But coffee was the drug of choice for England
Dialogue: 0,0:16:20.05,0:16:21.52,English1,,0,0,0,,in the 17th century.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:21.55,0:16:24.02,English1,,0,0,0,,Coffeehouses sprang up all over London.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:36.37,0:16:39.40,English1,,0,0,0,,This is where people came to get news,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:39.44,0:16:43.14,English1,,0,0,0,,to launch new ventures, and to debate ideas.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:43.17,0:16:45.54,English1,,0,0,0,,The coffeehouse was an oasis of equality
Dialogue: 0,0:16:45.58,0:16:48.21,English1,,0,0,0,,in a class-obsessed society.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:48.25,0:16:50.88,English1,,0,0,0,,Here, a poor man needn't give up his seat
Dialogue: 0,0:16:50.91,0:16:53.68,English1,,0,0,0,,to a rich man, nor submit to his opinion.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:53.72,0:16:56.02,English1,,0,0,0,,It was a kind of laboratory of democracy.
Dialogue: 0,0:16:56.05,0:16:58.69,English1,,0,0,0,,In this highly caffeinated atmosphere,
Dialogue: 0,0:16:58.72,0:17:03.43,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley and Hooke met Christopher\NWren to discuss a deep mystery.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:03.46,0:17:06.86,English1,,0,0,0,,Why do the planets move as they do?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:06.90,0:17:09.40,English1,,0,0,0,,The astronomer Johannes Kepler had demonstrated,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:09.43,0:17:10.90,English1,,0,0,0,,some 80 years before,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:10.93,0:17:13.50,English1,,0,0,0,,that the orbits of the planets around the Sun
Dialogue: 0,0:17:13.54,0:17:16.91,English1,,0,0,0,,were not perfect circles, but actually ellipses,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:16.94,0:17:20.21,English1,,0,0,0,,and that the closer a planet was to the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:20.24,0:17:23.18,English1,,0,0,0,,the faster it moved.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:23.21,0:17:25.07,English1,,0,0,0,,Why?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:25.48,0:17:28.05,English1,,0,0,0,,Could some invisible force\Nfrom the Sun be responsible
Dialogue: 0,0:17:28.05,0:17:29.69,English1,,0,0,0,,for this change in motion?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:29.69,0:17:31.42,English1,,0,0,0,,If so, how did it work?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:31.42,0:17:34.82,English1,,0,0,0,,Could there be a simple mathematical law to describe it?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:34.83,0:17:38.63,English1,,0,0,0,,Maybe something like Hooke's Law of Elasticity?
Dialogue: 0,0:17:42.17,0:17:43.93,English1,,0,0,0,,Perhaps.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:43.97,0:17:45.57,English1,,0,0,0,,But try as he might,
Dialogue: 0,0:17:45.60,0:17:46.90,English1,,0,0,0,,Christopher Wren couldn't figure it out.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:48.24,0:17:49.74,English1,,0,0,0,,Damned if I haven't tried.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:49.77,0:17:51.24,English1,,0,0,0,,It's beyond me.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:51.28,0:17:53.24,English1,,0,0,0,,I'll wager a book worth 40 shillings
Dialogue: 0,0:17:53.28,0:17:54.78,English1,,0,0,0,,to the man who can solve it!
Dialogue: 0,0:17:54.81,0:17:56.91,English1,,0,0,0,,That book is mine, Mr. Wren.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:56.95,0:17:58.28,English1,,0,0,0,,I've already done the calculation.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:58.32,0:17:59.62,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley was delighted.
Dialogue: 0,0:17:59.65,0:18:01.45,English1,,0,0,0,,Show us, Mr. Hooke.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:01.49,0:18:05.05,English1,,0,0,0,,But months passed, and Hooke failed to deliver.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:05.09,0:18:06.72,English1,,0,0,0,,He couldn't do the math.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:06.76,0:18:08.56,English1,,0,0,0,,None of them could.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:08.59,0:18:10.89,English1,,0,0,0,,Finally, Halley had enough of Hooke's excuses.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:10.93,0:18:13.96,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley knew there must be someone, somewhere,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:14.00,0:18:16.00,English1,,0,0,0,,up to the challenge.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:22.31,0:18:25.27,English1,,0,0,0,,What about that mathematician at Cambridge?
Dialogue: 0,0:18:25.31,0:18:27.11,English1,,0,0,0,,Clever fellow.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:27.14,0:18:29.48,English1,,0,0,0,,He had solved central questions about the nature of light
Dialogue: 0,0:18:29.51,0:18:33.32,English1,,0,0,0,,years before, when he was still only 22.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:33.35,0:18:35.28,English1,,0,0,0,,And he invented the reflecting telescope.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:35.32,0:18:36.99,English1,,0,0,0,,Odd bird.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:37.02,0:18:39.16,English1,,0,0,0,,Dropped out of sight a while back;
Dialogue: 0,0:18:39.19,0:18:42.29,English1,,0,0,0,,some squabble over Hooke\Nand his discovery about light.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:42.33,0:18:43.86,English1,,0,0,0,,Went completely to pieces over it
Dialogue: 0,0:18:43.89,0:18:46.43,English1,,0,0,0,,and has been hiding out\Nin Cambridge ever since.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:46.46,0:18:49.47,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley wondered if this strange, and by all accounts,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:49.50,0:18:52.10,English1,,0,0,0,,exceedingly difficult man, might succeed
Dialogue: 0,0:18:52.14,0:18:53.70,English1,,0,0,0,,where Hooke and others had failed.
Dialogue: 0,0:18:53.74,0:18:55.27,English1,,0,0,0,,What he couldn't know,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:55.31,0:18:58.27,English1,,0,0,0,,what no one could possibly\Nimagine at the time,
Dialogue: 0,0:18:58.31,0:18:59.81,English1,,0,0,0,,were the countless ways
Dialogue: 0,0:18:59.84,0:19:03.11,English1,,0,0,0,,the world would be forever\Nchanged by this meeting
Dialogue: 0,0:19:03.15,0:19:05.58,English1,,0,0,0,,on an August day in 1684.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:11.02,0:19:13.62,English1,,0,0,0,,Isaac Newton was born in England
Dialogue: 0,0:19:13.65,0:19:15.92,English1,,0,0,0,,on Christmas Day in 1642.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:17.86,0:19:21.80,English1,,0,0,0,,Before he even opened his eyes,\N{\i1}his father was already dead.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:23.83,0:19:26.73,English1,,0,0,0,,His mother left him when he was only three
Dialogue: 0,0:19:26.77,0:19:29.84,English1,,0,0,0,,and did not return until he was 11.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:29.87,0:19:33.64,English1,,0,0,0,,When she did, it was\N{\i1}with a new family and husband,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:33.67,0:19:36.28,English1,,0,0,0,,a stepfather who Isaac Newton despised.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:41.48,0:19:44.68,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton's refuge from his miserable family life
Dialogue: 0,0:19:44.72,0:19:48.52,English1,,0,0,0,,was his passion to understand how things worked,
Dialogue: 0,0:19:48.56,0:19:51.59,English1,,0,0,0,,especially nature itself.
Dialogue: 0,0:19:53.76,0:19:57.46,English1,,0,0,0,,In 1661, the talented young\N{\i1}Isaac entered Trinity College at Cambridge University
Dialogue: 0,0:19:57.50,0:20:00.13,English1,,0,0,0,,where he was a consistently lousy student,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:00.17,0:20:02.97,English1,,0,0,0,,one without friends or a loving family
Dialogue: 0,0:20:03.00,0:20:05.54,English1,,0,0,0,,to provide any warmth or encouragement.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:05.57,0:20:09.21,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton mostly kept to himself,\Nsequestered in his room,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:09.24,0:20:11.71,English1,,0,0,0,,studying ancient Greek philosophers,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:11.75,0:20:14.01,English1,,0,0,0,,geometry and languages,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:14.05,0:20:15.78,English1,,0,0,0,,and pondering deep questions
Dialogue: 0,0:20:15.82,0:20:20.79,English1,,0,0,0,,on the nature of matter, space, time, and motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:20.82,0:20:25.49,English1,,0,0,0,,This budding scientist was also a passionate mystic.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:25.53,0:20:27.19,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton believed that a secret knowledge
Dialogue: 0,0:20:27.23,0:20:29.53,English1,,0,0,0,,called alchemy, known only to a small group
Dialogue: 0,0:20:29.56,0:20:33.57,English1,,0,0,0,,of ancient philosophers,\N{\i1}was waiting to be rediscovered.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:33.60,0:20:37.24,English1,,0,0,0,,He hoped to learn how to change ordinary metals
Dialogue: 0,0:20:37.27,0:20:38.87,English1,,0,0,0,,into silver and gold,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:38.91,0:20:41.74,English1,,0,0,0,,and maybe even cook up the elixir of life,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:41.78,0:20:43.91,English1,,0,0,0,,the key to to immortality.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:44.91,0:20:47.81,English1,,0,0,0,,He was also obsessed
Dialogue: 0,0:20:47.85,0:20:51.05,English1,,0,0,0,,with finding hidden messages\N{\i1}in the words of the Bible.
Dialogue: 0,0:20:51.09,0:20:55.39,English1,,0,0,0,,He combed through translations\N{\i1}in several different languages,
Dialogue: 0,0:20:55.42,0:20:58.69,English1,,0,0,0,,hoping to decipher coded\N{\i1}instructions from God.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:04.90,0:21:07.10,English1,,0,0,0,,He made elaborate calculations\N{\i1}in an effort
Dialogue: 0,0:21:07.13,0:21:11.50,English1,,0,0,0,,to discover the date of the Second Coming.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:11.54,0:21:13.41,English1,,0,0,0,,His lifelong research in alchemy
Dialogue: 0,0:21:13.44,0:21:16.58,English1,,0,0,0,,and biblical chronology never led anywhere.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:21.25,0:21:24.08,English1,,0,0,0,,When Halley found Newton that fateful day,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:24.12,0:21:28.42,English1,,0,0,0,,he was living as a virtual recluse.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:31.06,0:21:33.96,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton had gone into hiding 13 years earlier,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:34.00,0:21:38.63,English1,,0,0,0,,after Robert Hooke had publicly\N{\i1}accused Newton of stealing
Dialogue: 0,0:21:38.67,0:21:40.87,English1,,0,0,0,,his groundbreaking work on light and color.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:40.90,0:21:43.90,English1,,0,0,0,,In fact, it was Isaac Newton
Dialogue: 0,0:21:43.94,0:21:45.77,English1,,0,0,0,,who solved the mystery of the spectrum of light,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:45.81,0:21:48.58,English1,,0,0,0,,not Robert Hooke.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:48.61,0:21:50.74,English1,,0,0,0,,This wound was painful and deep,
Dialogue: 0,0:21:50.78,0:21:53.55,English1,,0,0,0,,and Newton resolved to never\N{\i1}expose himself to that kind
Dialogue: 0,0:21:53.58,0:21:55.22,English1,,0,0,0,,of public humiliation ever again.
Dialogue: 0,0:21:55.25,0:21:58.25,English1,,0,0,0,,Sir, I don't suppose you recall
Dialogue: 0,0:21:58.29,0:22:00.29,English1,,0,0,0,,our meeting a few years ago?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:00.32,0:22:02.26,English1,,0,0,0,,Yes, Mr. Halley.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:02.29,0:22:03.79,English1,,0,0,0,,I'm sorry to bother you.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:03.82,0:22:06.66,English1,,0,0,0,,Never mind the formalities,\Nget to your point.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:06.69,0:22:09.93,English1,,0,0,0,,I've been talking with our\Nfriends, Mr. Wren and Mr. Hooke.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:09.96,0:22:12.93,English1,,0,0,0,,That scoundrel Hooke's\Nno friend of mine.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:12.97,0:22:14.73,English1,,0,0,0,,Yes, I understand, sir.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:14.77,0:22:16.77,English1,,0,0,0,,But the thing is we've been debating
Dialogue: 0,0:22:16.80,0:22:19.67,English1,,0,0,0,,the puzzling question of planetary motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:19.71,0:22:21.57,English1,,0,0,0,,We all agree that some force of attraction
Dialogue: 0,0:22:21.61,0:22:24.28,English1,,0,0,0,,from the Sun governs the motions of the planets.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:24.31,0:22:27.25,English1,,0,0,0,,We suspect there must be a mathematical law
Dialogue: 0,0:22:27.28,0:22:28.92,English1,,0,0,0,,to describe how this force
Dialogue: 0,0:22:28.95,0:22:31.42,English1,,0,0,0,,changes with distance.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:31.45,0:22:32.75,English1,,0,0,0,,And knowing of your skill...
Dialogue: 0,0:22:32.79,0:22:34.09,English1,,0,0,0,,Yes, yes, the attraction of gravity
Dialogue: 0,0:22:34.12,0:22:36.32,English1,,0,0,0,,weakens with the square of the distance.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:36.36,0:22:38.93,English1,,0,0,0,,That's why the planets move in ellipses.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:38.96,0:22:41.53,English1,,0,0,0,,But, sir, how can you know this?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:41.56,0:22:44.46,English1,,0,0,0,,Why, I have calculated it some five years ago.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:44.50,0:22:47.37,English1,,0,0,0,,I beg you, show it to me.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:47.40,0:22:48.77,English1,,0,0,0,,The calculation is here...
Dialogue: 0,0:22:48.80,0:22:50.77,English1,,0,0,0,,somewhere.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:50.81,0:22:52.01,English1,,0,0,0,,Well, no matter.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:52.04,0:22:53.47,English1,,0,0,0,,I shall redo it and be sure
Dialogue: 0,0:22:53.51,0:22:54.54,English1,,0,0,0,,to send it on to you.
Dialogue: 0,0:22:54.58,0:22:56.01,English1,,0,0,0,,This is stupendous!
Dialogue: 0,0:22:56.04,0:22:58.31,English1,,0,0,0,,Why have we not had word of it before?
Dialogue: 0,0:22:58.35,0:23:00.15,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton remembered all too well
Dialogue: 0,0:23:00.18,0:23:03.18,English1,,0,0,0,,what Hooke had done to him
Dialogue: 0,0:23:03.22,0:23:05.85,English1,,0,0,0,,the last time he put forth an idea.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:05.89,0:23:07.95,English1,,0,0,0,,Just when Halley may have begun to wonder
Dialogue: 0,0:23:07.99,0:23:11.12,English1,,0,0,0,,if Newton was bluffing as Hooke had done earlier,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:11.16,0:23:15.00,English1,,0,0,0,,a messenger arrived\Nwith an envelope from Newton.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:17.90,0:23:21.67,English1,,0,0,0,,Here are the opening pages\Nof modern science
Dialogue: 0,0:23:21.70,0:23:24.97,English1,,0,0,0,,with its all-embracing vision of nature...
Dialogue: 0,0:23:25.01,0:23:28.74,English1,,0,0,0,,universal laws of motion, gravity...
Dialogue: 0,0:23:28.78,0:23:30.38,English1,,0,0,0,,not just for the Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:23:30.41,0:23:33.35,English1,,0,0,0,,but for the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:33.38,0:23:36.65,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley raced back to Cambridge.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:36.68,0:23:39.72,English1,,0,0,0,,Mr. Newton, I beseech you\Nto work all of this
Dialogue: 0,0:23:39.75,0:23:42.32,English1,,0,0,0,,into a book as soon as possible.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:42.36,0:23:45.83,English1,,0,0,0,,I can assure you the Royal\NSociety will publish it.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:45.86,0:23:47.69,English1,,0,0,0,,But there was one little problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:47.73,0:23:50.16,English1,,0,0,0,,We are in agreement
Dialogue: 0,0:23:50.20,0:23:53.33,English1,,0,0,0,,that Mr. Newton has produced a masterpiece.
Dialogue: 0,0:23:53.37,0:23:57.00,English1,,0,0,0,,However, I'm afraid the Royal Society has...
Dialogue: 0,0:23:57.04,0:24:00.94,English1,,0,0,0,,well, regrettably sales for the{\i1} History of Fish...
Dialogue: 0,0:24:00.98,0:24:04.88,English1,,0,0,0,,have not lived up to our financial expectations.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:04.91,0:24:07.71,English1,,0,0,0,,It's an impressive book.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:07.75,0:24:09.62,English1,,0,0,0,,Extremely comprehensive.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:09.65,0:24:11.42,English1,,0,0,0,,Really.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:11.45,0:24:14.96,English1,,0,0,0,,It's filled with lavish illustrations of...
Dialogue: 0,0:24:14.99,0:24:18.43,English1,,0,0,0,,well, fish.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:18.46,0:24:20.86,English1,,0,0,0,,The disappointing sales led to a bigger problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:20.90,0:24:23.40,English1,,0,0,0,,The Royal Society pretty much blew
Dialogue: 0,0:24:23.43,0:24:26.40,English1,,0,0,0,,its total annual budget on the{\i1} History of Fish.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:26.43,0:24:29.14,English1,,0,0,0,,In fact, they were so strapped for cash,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:29.17,0:24:31.57,English1,,0,0,0,,they had to pay poor Halley's salary
Dialogue: 0,0:24:31.61,0:24:34.27,English1,,0,0,0,,with copies of their worst-selling book.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:34.31,0:24:37.48,English1,,0,0,0,,With no money to print\NNewton's{\i1} Principia,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:37.51,0:24:40.61,English1,,0,0,0,,the scientific revolution\Nhung in the balance.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:43.11,0:24:45.01,English1,,0,0,0,,Without Halley's heroic efforts,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:45.09,0:24:47.15,English1,,0,0,0,,the reclusive Newton's masterwork
Dialogue: 0,0:24:47.24,0:24:49.26,English1,,0,0,0,,might never have seen the light of day.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:49.60,0:24:51.80,English1,,0,0,0,,But Halley was a man on a mission,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:51.80,0:24:55.41,English1,,0,0,0,,absolutely determined to bring\NNewton's genius to the world.
Dialogue: 0,0:24:55.41,0:24:57.98,English1,,0,0,0,,That pre-scientific world,
Dialogue: 0,0:24:57.98,0:25:00.44,English1,,0,0,0,,the world ruled by fear,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:00.45,0:25:03.58,English1,,0,0,0,,was poised at the edge of a revolution.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:03.58,0:25:06.95,English1,,0,0,0,,Everything depended\N{\i1}on whether or not Edmond Halley
Dialogue: 0,0:25:06.95,0:25:09.95,English1,,0,0,0,,could get Newton's book out to the wider world.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:09.96,0:25:12.76,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley resolved not only to edit Newton's book,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:12.76,0:25:15.76,English1,,0,0,0,,but to publish it at his own expense.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:15.76,0:25:17.66,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton completed the first two volumes,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:17.66,0:25:19.86,English1,,0,0,0,,laying the mathematical framework
Dialogue: 0,0:25:19.87,0:25:22.43,English1,,0,0,0,,for the physics of motion.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:22.44,0:25:25.47,English1,,0,0,0,,The third volume would settle once and for all
Dialogue: 0,0:25:25.47,0:25:27.34,English1,,0,0,0,,who won the coffeehouse wager.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:27.34,0:25:29.61,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton applied his principles to explain
Dialogue: 0,0:25:29.61,0:25:31.74,English1,,0,0,0,,all the known motions of the Earth,
Dialogue: 0,0:25:31.74,0:25:34.11,English1,,0,0,0,,the Moon and the planets.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:34.11,0:25:37.08,English1,,0,0,0,,Unfortunately, there was this problem.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:37.12,0:25:38.92,English1,,0,0,0,,Now Halley also took on the role
Dialogue: 0,0:25:38.95,0:25:41.85,English1,,0,0,0,,of Newton's psychotherapist.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:41.89,0:25:45.22,English1,,0,0,0,,Isaac, I'm afraid that Mr. Hooke requires
Dialogue: 0,0:25:45.26,0:25:48.56,English1,,0,0,0,,an acknowledgment in\Nthe preface of your third volume.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:48.59,0:25:49.89,English1,,0,0,0,,But I have done so.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:49.93,0:25:52.03,English1,,0,0,0,,Thanking him, Mr. Wren and yourself
Dialogue: 0,0:25:52.06,0:25:55.13,English1,,0,0,0,,for prodding me to think again\Non astronomical matters.
Dialogue: 0,0:25:55.17,0:25:58.37,English1,,0,0,0,,Mr. Hooke has been going about London saying
Dialogue: 0,0:25:58.40,0:26:00.87,English1,,0,0,0,,that you got the Law of Gravity from him.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:00.91,0:26:02.47,English1,,0,0,0,,Why, that litigious little...
Dialogue: 0,0:26:02.51,0:26:03.81,English1,,0,0,0,,Never!
Dialogue: 0,0:26:03.84,0:26:05.64,English1,,0,0,0,,I would sooner burn the third volume
Dialogue: 0,0:26:05.68,0:26:07.65,English1,,0,0,0,,than deface it with such a lie.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:07.68,0:26:09.11,English1,,0,0,0,,To hell with Hooke.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:09.15,0:26:10.45,English1,,0,0,0,,He will be long forgotten
Dialogue: 0,0:26:10.48,0:26:12.78,English1,,0,0,0,,when your ideas are still being celebrated.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:14.65,0:26:18.72,English1,,0,0,0,,More copies of that dreadful book?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:18.76,0:26:21.46,English1,,0,0,0,,Wherever shall we put them all?
Dialogue: 0,0:26:21.49,0:26:22.99,English1,,0,0,0,,We talked about this, Mary, dear.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:23.03,0:26:25.66,English1,,0,0,0,,This is my salary from the Society.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:25.70,0:26:28.47,English1,,0,0,0,,They have nothing else with which to pay me.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:28.50,0:26:30.73,English1,,0,0,0,,If only Mr. Hooke and Mr. Newton were more like you.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:30.77,0:26:32.77,English1,,0,0,0,,If only Mr. Hooke and Mr. Newton were more like you.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:32.80,0:26:34.77,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley and Wren decided to confront Hooke
Dialogue: 0,0:26:34.81,0:26:36.44,English1,,0,0,0,,about his false claims.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:36.47,0:26:39.08,English1,,0,0,0,,That law is mine, I tell you!
Dialogue: 0,0:26:39.11,0:26:40.44,English1,,0,0,0,,I proved it first.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:40.48,0:26:42.28,English1,,0,0,0,,Then fetch your proof here at once.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:42.31,0:26:43.51,English1,,0,0,0,,Let us see it.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:43.55,0:26:47.12,English1,,0,0,0,,Surely we have waited on it long enough.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:47.15,0:26:50.25,English1,,0,0,0,,You'll simply have to take my word for it.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:50.29,0:26:52.66,English1,,0,0,0,,Empty claims may persuade elsewhere,
Dialogue: 0,0:26:52.69,0:26:54.86,English1,,0,0,0,,but not here.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:54.89,0:26:57.49,English1,,0,0,0,,Put up or shut up, Mr. Hooke.
Dialogue: 0,0:26:59.40,0:27:01.53,English1,,0,0,0,,Blasted Newton. I'll make him pay.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:16.55,0:27:19.98,English1,,0,0,0,,If it wasn't for Edmond Halley,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:20.02,0:27:22.15,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton's great book would've\Nnever been conceived,
Dialogue: 0,0:27:22.19,0:27:24.69,English1,,0,0,0,,nor written, nor printed.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:24.72,0:27:26.99,English1,,0,0,0,,Okay. So what?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:27.03,0:27:29.16,English1,,0,0,0,,What difference does that make to us?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:29.19,0:27:31.96,English1,,0,0,0,,What's the big deal?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:38.24,0:27:41.37,English1,,0,0,0,,When Isaac Newton was born in this house
Dialogue: 0,0:27:41.38,0:27:44.04,English1,,0,0,0,,in 1642, the world was very different.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:44.08,0:27:46.28,English1,,0,0,0,,Everyone looked at the perfection
Dialogue: 0,0:27:46.31,0:27:48.95,English1,,0,0,0,,of the clockwork motions of the planets in the sky
Dialogue: 0,0:27:48.98,0:27:50.88,English1,,0,0,0,,and could only understand it as the work
Dialogue: 0,0:27:50.92,0:27:52.55,English1,,0,0,0,,of a master clock maker.
Dialogue: 0,0:27:52.58,0:27:54.65,English1,,0,0,0,,How else to explain it?
Dialogue: 0,0:27:54.69,0:27:57.02,English1,,0,0,0,,There was only one way\Nsuch a thing could come about
Dialogue: 0,0:27:57.06,0:27:58.49,English1,,0,0,0,,in their imagination;
Dialogue: 0,0:27:58.52,0:28:00.52,English1,,0,0,0,,only one answer for them--
Dialogue: 0,0:28:00.56,0:28:01.99,English1,,0,0,0,,God.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:02.03,0:28:04.29,English1,,0,0,0,,For reasons beyond our understanding,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:04.33,0:28:06.86,English1,,0,0,0,,God just created the solar system that way.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:06.90,0:28:09.83,English1,,0,0,0,,But this explanation is the closing of a door.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:09.87,0:28:13.40,English1,,0,0,0,,It doesn't lead to other questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:23.55,0:28:24.85,English1,,0,0,0,,Along came Newton,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:24.88,0:28:27.99,English1,,0,0,0,,a God-loving man\Nwho's also a genius.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:28.02,0:28:30.15,English1,,0,0,0,,He could write the laws of nature
Dialogue: 0,0:28:30.19,0:28:32.59,English1,,0,0,0,,in perfect mathematical sentences--
Dialogue: 0,0:28:32.62,0:28:35.06,English1,,0,0,0,,formulas that applied universally
Dialogue: 0,0:28:35.09,0:28:38.03,English1,,0,0,0,,to apples, moons, planets
Dialogue: 0,0:28:38.06,0:28:40.23,English1,,0,0,0,,and so much more.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:42.27,0:28:45.10,English1,,0,0,0,,With one foot still in the Middle Ages,
Dialogue: 0,0:28:45.14,0:28:48.37,English1,,0,0,0,,Isaac Newton imagined the whole solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:48.41,0:28:50.74,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton's laws of gravity and motion
Dialogue: 0,0:28:50.78,0:28:54.61,English1,,0,0,0,,revealed how the Sun held distant worlds captive.
Dialogue: 0,0:28:54.65,0:28:56.78,English1,,0,0,0,,His laws swept away the need
Dialogue: 0,0:28:56.81,0:28:58.42,English1,,0,0,0,,for a master clock maker
Dialogue: 0,0:28:58.45,0:29:01.89,English1,,0,0,0,,to explain the precision\Nand beauty of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:01.92,0:29:05.12,English1,,0,0,0,,Gravity is the clock maker.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:05.16,0:29:08.53,English1,,0,0,0,,Matter obeyed commandments\Nwe could discover,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:08.56,0:29:11.13,English1,,0,0,0,,laws the Bible hadn't mentioned.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:11.16,0:29:14.13,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton's answer to why the\Nsolar system is the way it is
Dialogue: 0,0:29:14.17,0:29:17.70,English1,,0,0,0,,opened the way to an infinite number of questions.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:17.74,0:29:19.74,English1,,0,0,0,,Principia also happened to include
Dialogue: 0,0:29:19.77,0:29:21.74,English1,,0,0,0,,the invention of calculus,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:21.77,0:29:24.37,English1,,0,0,0,,and the first sound theoretical basis
Dialogue: 0,0:29:24.41,0:29:26.88,English1,,0,0,0,,for an end to our imprisonment on Earth--
Dialogue: 0,0:29:26.91,0:29:29.08,English1,,0,0,0,,space travel.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:32.48,0:29:35.15,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton envisioned the firing of a cannonball...
Dialogue: 0,0:29:36.96,0:29:39.46,English1,,0,0,0,,with increasingly greater explosive thrust.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:41.93,0:29:45.30,English1,,0,0,0,,He reasoned that with enough velocity,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:45.33,0:29:47.90,English1,,0,0,0,,the bounds of gravity could be broken,
Dialogue: 0,0:29:47.93,0:29:49.83,English1,,0,0,0,,and the cannonball could escape
Dialogue: 0,0:29:49.87,0:29:52.17,English1,,0,0,0,,to orbit the Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:29:52.20,0:29:55.31,English1,,0,0,0,,This changed everything.
Dialogue: 0,0:30:57.24,0:31:01.81,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton's Principia Mathematica\N{\i1}set us free in another way.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:01.84,0:31:03.71,English1,,0,0,0,,By finding the natural laws
Dialogue: 0,0:31:03.74,0:31:06.51,English1,,0,0,0,,governing the comings and goings of comets,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:06.54,0:31:08.65,English1,,0,0,0,,he decoupled the motions\N{\i1}of the heavens
Dialogue: 0,0:31:08.68,0:31:12.42,English1,,0,0,0,,from their ancient connections to our fears.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:14.98,0:31:18.26,English1,,0,0,0,,If Halley hadn't been standing\Nnext to Newton for all those years,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:18.29,0:31:23.30,English1,,0,0,0,,perhaps the world would remember him\Nfor his own accomplishments and discoveries.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:23.33,0:31:26.43,English1,,0,0,0,,But the only thing that comes\Nto mind for most people
Dialogue: 0,0:31:26.47,0:31:30.92,English1,,0,0,0,,is the comet, the irony is that discovering a comet
Dialogue: 0,0:31:30.95,0:31:34.84,English1,,0,0,0,,is actually one of the few things that Halley never did.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:47.51,0:31:50.13,English1,,0,0,0,,After the publication of the Principia
Dialogue: 0,0:31:50.16,0:31:54.01,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley was commanded by\Nhis king to lead three ocean voyages,
Dialogue: 0,0:31:54.05,0:31:58.58,English1,,0,0,0,,scientific expeditions to solve\Nnavigational problems for the British navy.
Dialogue: 0,0:31:58.62,0:32:04.25,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley used this opportunity to make\Nthe first map of the Earth's magnetic field
Dialogue: 0,0:32:08.01,0:32:10.88,English1,,0,0,0,,And he was also a businessman.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:12.98,0:32:15.78,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley perfected the diving bell...
Dialogue: 0,0:32:17.32,0:32:19.42,English1,,0,0,0,,...and used his invention to start
Dialogue: 0,0:32:19.45,0:32:22.52,English1,,0,0,0,,a flourishing commercial salvage operation.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:26.80,0:32:28.96,English1,,0,0,0,,Mmm, ah, Dr. Halley's gone and done it this time.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:29.00,0:32:32.20,English1,,0,0,0,,I reckon he's been down there at least three hours.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:32.23,0:32:34.94,English1,,0,0,0,,Not one to risk the lives of others,
Dialogue: 0,0:32:34.97,0:32:38.37,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley personally tested his own invention.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:42.01,0:32:45.51,English1,,0,0,0,,I make it exactly four hours since our descent.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:45.55,0:32:47.65,English1,,0,0,0,,Not at all bad for ten fathoms.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:52.99,0:32:54.92,English1,,0,0,0,,He invented the weather map.
Dialogue: 0,0:32:57.69,0:33:01.23,English1,,0,0,0,,And the symbols he devised\N{\i1}for indicating prevailing winds
Dialogue: 0,0:33:01.26,0:33:03.70,English1,,0,0,0,,are still in use today.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:13.41,0:33:16.04,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley laid the groundwork
Dialogue: 0,0:33:16.08,0:33:18.15,English1,,0,0,0,,for the science of population statistics.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:18.18,0:33:19.48,English1,,0,0,0,,How?
Dialogue: 0,0:33:19.51,0:33:22.48,English1,,0,0,0,,He compared the birth, marriage, death,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:22.52,0:33:25.39,English1,,0,0,0,,and population densities\Nof London and Paris.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:25.42,0:33:27.69,English1,,0,0,0,,He actually had to pace off
Dialogue: 0,0:33:27.72,0:33:28.86,English1,,0,0,0,,the entire perimeter of Paris, on foot,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:28.89,0:33:31.09,English1,,0,0,0,,to learn its true dimensions.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:31.13,0:33:32.49,English1,,0,0,0,,He came to the conclusion
Dialogue: 0,0:33:32.53,0:33:34.23,English1,,0,0,0,,that since roughly half of all adults fail
Dialogue: 0,0:33:34.26,0:33:35.70,English1,,0,0,0,,to reproduce children,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:35.73,0:33:37.70,English1,,0,0,0,,who themselves survive to reproduce,
Dialogue: 0,0:33:37.73,0:33:40.60,English1,,0,0,0,,every married couple must have four children
Dialogue: 0,0:33:40.64,0:33:43.10,English1,,0,0,0,,in order to maintain the population.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:46.11,0:33:48.71,English1,,0,0,0,,And it was Edmond Halley who gave us
Dialogue: 0,0:33:48.74,0:33:50.34,English1,,0,0,0,,the actual scale of the solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:50.38,0:33:52.91,English1,,0,0,0,,He figured out a clever way\Nto find the distance
Dialogue: 0,0:33:52.95,0:33:54.45,English1,,0,0,0,,from Earth to the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:33:54.48,0:33:56.72,English1,,0,0,0,,It involved precisely measuring the time it took
Dialogue: 0,0:33:56.75,0:34:00.09,English1,,0,0,0,,for the planet Venus to cross the Sun's disc.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:03.06,0:34:05.86,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}27 years after Halley's death,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:05.89,0:34:09.23,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Captain James Cook made{\i}\N{\i1}his first voyage to Tahiti
Dialogue: 0,0:34:09.26,0:34:11.80,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}for the express purpose{\i}\N{\i1}of testing Halley's method
Dialogue: 0,0:34:11.83,0:34:14.40,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}during a transit of Venus{\i}\N{\i1}across the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:14.44,0:34:16.80,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Using a special filter{\i}\N{\i1}to protect his vision
Dialogue: 0,0:34:16.84,0:34:19.97,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}from being destroyed{\i}\N{\i1}by looking directly at the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:34:20.01,0:34:22.71,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Cook and his men made it{\i}\N{\i1}possible for us to know
Dialogue: 0,0:34:22.74,0:34:27.05,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}that the Sun is 93 million miles from Earth.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:27.08,0:34:29.45,English1,,0,0,0,,And Halley was the first to realize
Dialogue: 0,0:34:29.48,0:34:33.32,English1,,0,0,0,,that the so-called "fixed" stars were not fixed at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:33.36,0:34:35.12,English1,,0,0,0,,How'd he do it?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:35.16,0:34:37.73,English1,,0,0,0,,He pored over the observations made
Dialogue: 0,0:34:37.76,0:34:40.39,English1,,0,0,0,,by the ancient Greek astronomers of the brightest stars.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:40.43,0:34:43.13,English1,,0,0,0,,And he compared their\Nobservations with the ones
Dialogue: 0,0:34:43.16,0:34:47.17,English1,,0,0,0,,he himself made of the same stars 1,800 years later.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:47.20,0:34:49.44,English1,,0,0,0,,Why hadn't anyone noticed\Nthis before?
Dialogue: 0,0:34:49.47,0:34:52.44,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley figured out that it would only become apparent
Dialogue: 0,0:34:52.47,0:34:55.58,English1,,0,0,0,,if you waited long enough between observations.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:55.61,0:34:58.11,English1,,0,0,0,,It's hard to perceive the motions of things
Dialogue: 0,0:34:58.15,0:34:59.45,English1,,0,0,0,,that are far away.
Dialogue: 0,0:34:59.48,0:35:02.15,English1,,0,0,0,,And the stars are so very far away,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:02.18,0:35:04.49,English1,,0,0,0,,that you would need to track them for many centuries
Dialogue: 0,0:35:04.52,0:35:07.86,English1,,0,0,0,,before you could detect that they moved at all.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:09.79,0:35:13.43,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}Halley discovered the first clue to a magnificent reality,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:13.46,0:35:17.87,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}all the stars are in motion, streaming past each other,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:17.90,0:35:20.53,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}rising and falling like merry-go-round horses
Dialogue: 0,0:35:20.57,0:35:26.31,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}in their Newtonian dance around the center of our galaxy.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:26.34,0:35:30.54,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}And, oh, yes, there was that thing about the comet.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:34.32,0:35:37.79,English1,,0,0,0,,What were those strange and\Nbeautiful celestial visitors
Dialogue: 0,0:35:37.82,0:35:40.39,English1,,0,0,0,,that appeared without warning from time to time?
Dialogue: 0,0:35:40.42,0:35:44.49,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley set out to solve this\Nmystery as a detective would,
Dialogue: 0,0:35:44.53,0:35:46.83,English1,,0,0,0,,by gathering all credible eyewitness testimony.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:46.86,0:35:49.40,English1,,0,0,0,,The earliest precise observations of a comet
Dialogue: 0,0:35:49.43,0:35:52.30,English1,,0,0,0,,that Halley could find were made in Constantinople
Dialogue: 0,0:35:52.33,0:35:56.64,English1,,0,0,0,,by Nikephoros Gregoras, a Byzantine astronomer and monk
Dialogue: 0,0:35:56.67,0:35:58.91,English1,,0,0,0,,in June 1337.
Dialogue: 0,0:35:58.94,0:36:02.21,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley hunted down every astronomical observation
Dialogue: 0,0:36:02.24,0:36:08.08,English1,,0,0,0,,of a comet recorded in Europe between 1472 and 1698.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:08.12,0:36:11.19,English1,,0,0,0,,And remember, there was no such thing
Dialogue: 0,0:36:11.22,0:36:13.02,English1,,0,0,0,,as a search engine or a computer.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:13.05,0:36:16.26,English1,,0,0,0,,All Halley had\Nwere his books and his mind.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:16.29,0:36:18.09,English1,,0,0,0,,Now here comes the hard part,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:18.13,0:36:21.10,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley had to take the\Nobservations made for each comet
Dialogue: 0,0:36:21.13,0:36:25.23,English1,,0,0,0,,and find the shape of its\Nactual path through space.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:25.27,0:36:27.33,English1,,0,0,0,,No one else but Newton had yet attempted
Dialogue: 0,0:36:27.37,0:36:30.67,English1,,0,0,0,,to apply his new set of laws to an astronomical question.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:30.71,0:36:34.01,English1,,0,0,0,,In an arduous tour de force of mathematical brilliance,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:34.04,0:36:38.38,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley discovered that comets were bound to the Sun
Dialogue: 0,0:36:38.41,0:36:40.65,English1,,0,0,0,,in long elliptical orbits.
Dialogue: 0,0:36:44.45,0:36:49.09,English1,,0,0,0,,And he was the first to know\Nthat the comets seen in 1531,
Dialogue: 0,0:36:49.12,0:36:54.96,English1,,0,0,0,,1607, and 1682...
Dialogue: 0,0:36:55.00,0:36:56.96,English1,,0,0,0,,were one and the same--
Dialogue: 0,0:36:57.00,0:37:00.20,English1,,0,0,0,,a single comet that returned every 76 years.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:00.24,0:37:03.57,English1,,0,0,0,,In a stunning example\Nof true pattern recognition,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:03.61,0:37:06.57,English1,,0,0,0,,he predicted\Nit would be seen again
Dialogue: 0,0:37:06.61,0:37:08.78,English1,,0,0,0,,more than 50 years in the future.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:10.48,0:37:13.55,English1,,0,0,0,,{\i1}For millennia, comets had been props for mystics,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:13.58,0:37:18.15,English1,,0,0,0,,who considered them to be\N{\i1}merely omens of human events.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:18.19,0:37:19.95,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley shattered their monopoly,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:19.99,0:37:22.42,English1,,0,0,0,,beating them at their own game,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:22.46,0:37:26.09,English1,,0,0,0,,a game that no scientist\Nhad ever played before...
Dialogue: 0,0:37:26.13,0:37:27.80,English1,,0,0,0,,prophecy.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:27.83,0:37:30.13,English1,,0,0,0,,And he did not hedge his bet.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:30.17,0:37:31.73,English1,,0,0,0,,Like Babe Ruth predicting
Dialogue: 0,0:37:31.77,0:37:34.57,English1,,0,0,0,,where his next home run would land in the stands,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:34.60,0:37:37.50,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley stated flatly that the comet would return
Dialogue: 0,0:37:37.54,0:37:42.11,English1,,0,0,0,,at the end of 1758, from a particular part of the sky,
Dialogue: 0,0:37:42.14,0:37:44.41,English1,,0,0,0,,following a specific path.
Dialogue: 0,0:37:44.45,0:37:47.18,English1,,0,0,0,,There is hardly a prophecy attempted by the mystics
Dialogue: 0,0:37:47.22,0:37:50.35,English1,,0,0,0,,that ever even strives for comparable precision.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:08.46,0:38:10.50,English1,,0,0,0,,That's Halley's Comet.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:10.53,0:38:12.93,English1,,0,0,0,,Out here at the edge of the solar system,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:12.97,0:38:14.34,English1,,0,0,0,,it doesn't look like much.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:14.37,0:38:17.84,English1,,0,0,0,,Just a big hunk of ice and rock in space.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:17.87,0:38:19.87,English1,,0,0,0,,That's because beyond the orbit of Neptune,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:19.91,0:38:22.38,English1,,0,0,0,,nearly five billion kilometers from the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:22.41,0:38:24.88,English1,,0,0,0,,comets lead very quiet lives.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:27.38,0:38:30.65,English1,,0,0,0,,As it reaches the far end of its orbit,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:30.69,0:38:33.65,English1,,0,0,0,,it'll slow down till the Sun\Nallows it to go no farther.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:33.69,0:38:38.36,English1,,0,0,0,,Then it will begin its long fall\Nback to the inner solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:38.39,0:38:42.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley's comet is in free fall around the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:42.03,0:38:45.37,English1,,0,0,0,,Everything in our solar system--\Nthe Earth, the Moon,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:45.40,0:38:47.47,English1,,0,0,0,,the other planets, comets, asteroids,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:47.50,0:38:50.70,English1,,0,0,0,,all of them are falling around the Sun.
Dialogue: 0,0:38:50.74,0:38:53.74,English1,,0,0,0,,Gravity pulls the planets towards the Sun,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:53.78,0:38:55.68,English1,,0,0,0,,but because of their orbital momentum,
Dialogue: 0,0:38:55.71,0:38:59.71,English1,,0,0,0,,they keep moving around the Sun,\Nnever falling into it.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:03.72,0:39:05.85,English1,,0,0,0,,Robert Hooke had died years before,
Dialogue: 0,0:39:05.89,0:39:08.66,English1,,0,0,0,,having ruined his health\N{\i1}with some bad habits...
Dialogue: 0,0:39:08.69,0:39:12.69,English1,,0,0,0,,daily doses of wormwood,\N{\i1}opium, mercury.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:12.73,0:39:15.86,English1,,0,0,0,,A few months later, Newton was\N{\i1}elected to replace him
Dialogue: 0,0:39:15.90,0:39:18.10,English1,,0,0,0,,as president of the Royal Society.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:18.13,0:39:20.87,English1,,0,0,0,,It is said that a portrait of Hooke
Dialogue: 0,0:39:20.90,0:39:23.67,English1,,0,0,0,,once hung on these walls.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:23.71,0:39:28.21,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley lived on to accomplish\N{\i1}many more astonishing feats.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:28.24,0:39:32.88,English1,,0,0,0,,He worked right up to his death at age 85.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:32.91,0:39:36.42,English1,,0,0,0,,His final act was to call for a glass of wine.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:36.45,0:39:38.79,English1,,0,0,0,,He downed it with pleasure...
Dialogue: 0,0:39:38.82,0:39:40.96,English1,,0,0,0,,and breathed his last breath.
Dialogue: 0,0:39:46.09,0:39:50.06,English1,,0,0,0,,Some believe that it was on a night like this
Dialogue: 0,0:39:50.10,0:39:53.07,English1,,0,0,0,,that Isaac Newton finally took his revenge
Dialogue: 0,0:39:53.10,0:39:54.94,English1,,0,0,0,,against Robert Hooke.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:09.48,0:40:11.95,English1,,0,0,0,,But Halley's prophecy was not forgotten.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:11.99,0:40:13.55,English1,,0,0,0,,50 years later,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:13.59,0:40:16.22,English1,,0,0,0,,as the time of the predicted return approached,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:16.26,0:40:17.99,English1,,0,0,0,,the world's astronomers vied
Dialogue: 0,0:40:18.03,0:40:20.90,English1,,0,0,0,,to be the first to catch sight of his comet.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:20.93,0:40:22.50,English1,,0,0,0,,They weren't disappointed.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:22.53,0:40:26.77,English1,,0,0,0,,It's been welcomed back every 76 years since.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:26.80,0:40:30.17,English1,,0,0,0,,When Halley's Comet returns to our skies,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:30.21,0:40:33.24,English1,,0,0,0,,sunlight will warm up the ice on its surface,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:33.28,0:40:35.24,English1,,0,0,0,,once again setting loose
Dialogue: 0,0:40:35.28,0:40:39.18,English1,,0,0,0,,the dust and gases trapped within.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:41.15,0:40:43.62,English1,,0,0,0,,Halley's Comet most recently visited our neighborhood
Dialogue: 0,0:40:43.65,0:40:46.49,English1,,0,0,0,,back in 1986.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:46.52,0:40:49.59,English1,,0,0,0,,And if you're seeing this in 2061,
Dialogue: 0,0:40:49.62,0:40:51.56,English1,,0,0,0,,then you'll know it's back.
Dialogue: 0,0:40:54.13,0:40:55.96,English1,,0,0,0,,May you feel the wonder of all those
Dialogue: 0,0:40:56.00,0:40:58.37,English1,,0,0,0,,who came before you...
Dialogue: 0,0:40:58.40,0:41:00.37,English1,,0,0,0,,and none of the fear.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:00.40,0:41:04.00,English1,,0,0,0,,Newton's laws made it possible for Edmond Halley
Dialogue: 0,0:41:04.04,0:41:06.71,English1,,0,0,0,,to see some 50 years into the future
Dialogue: 0,0:41:06.74,0:41:09.71,English1,,0,0,0,,and predict the behavior of a single comet.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:09.74,0:41:13.05,English1,,0,0,0,,Scientists have been using these laws ever since,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:13.08,0:41:15.95,English1,,0,0,0,,opening the way to the Moon
Dialogue: 0,0:41:15.98,0:41:18.99,English1,,0,0,0,,and even beyond our solar system.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:19.02,0:41:21.76,English1,,0,0,0,,The baby in the basket is learning to walk...
Dialogue: 0,0:41:28.23,0:41:30.77,English1,,0,0,0,,and to know the cosmos.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:35.64,0:41:37.97,English1,,0,0,0,,Which brings me to one last prophecy.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:38.01,0:41:41.14,English1,,0,0,0,,Using nothing more than Newton's laws of gravitation,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:41.18,0:41:43.84,English1,,0,0,0,,we astronomers can confidently predict
Dialogue: 0,0:41:43.88,0:41:46.15,English1,,0,0,0,,that several billion years from now,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:46.18,0:41:48.88,English1,,0,0,0,,our home galaxy, the Milky Way,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:48.92,0:41:53.22,English1,,0,0,0,,will merge with our neighboring galaxy Andromeda.
Dialogue: 0,0:41:54.79,0:41:56.99,English1,,0,0,0,,Because the distances between the stars
Dialogue: 0,0:41:57.03,0:41:59.36,English1,,0,0,0,,are so great compared to their sizes,
Dialogue: 0,0:41:59.39,0:42:02.83,English1,,0,0,0,,few if any stars in either\N{\i1}galaxy will actually collide.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:02.86,0:42:05.77,English1,,0,0,0,,Any life on the worlds of that far-off future
Dialogue: 0,0:42:05.80,0:42:09.74,English1,,0,0,0,,should be safe, but they would\N{\i1}be treated to an amazing,
Dialogue: 0,0:42:09.77,0:42:13.74,English1,,0,0,0,,billion-year-long light show...
Dialogue: 0,0:42:13.78,0:42:17.41,English1,,0,0,0,,a dance of a half a trillion stars...
Dialogue: 0,0:42:17.45,0:42:26.95,English1,,0,0,0,,to music first heard on one little world\Nby a man who had but one true friend.
Dialogue: 0,0:42:30.56,0:42:40.47,English1,,0,0,0,,Sync and corrections by n17t01\Nwww.addic7ed.com
